                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d497">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/12542: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Canton (<persName type="from"
                            >Ballantine</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Canton</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-11-28T10:00:00+08:00"
                            >November 28, 1933—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 28—3 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>My November 18, 5 p.m.<note n="97" xml:id="d497fn97">Not printed.</note> Marshal
                    Chen informed me yesterday that delegates who had arrived from Fukien to urge
                    Canton to join movement were told that Canton could not do this as the Fukien
                    leaders were cooperating with the Communists and Japanese. Public manifestoes
                    are of a similar tenor but harp also on Fukien’s repudiation of the
                    Kuomintang.</p>
                <p>Public uneasiness appears subsiding.</p>
                <p>Repeated to the Department, the Legation and to Nanking.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Ballantine</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
